40|$|Host country governments often grant <b>tax</b> <b>holidays</b> {{to foreign}} firms located in their territories. Although such {{preferential}} tax treatment appears to disadvantage local competitors who try to enter the new markets, <b>tax</b> <b>holidays</b> can actually facilitate entry by local firms. This procompetitive effect {{stems from the fact}} that <b>tax</b> <b>holidays</b> are granted for a limited time. By making the foreign firm appear temporarily "tough," <b>tax</b> <b>holidays</b> induce local firms to delay entry, which in turn prompts the foreign firm to accommodate entry rather than pursue costly entry-deterring strategies. Thus, <b>tax</b> <b>holidays</b> benefit both the foreign firms and local entrepreneurs. ...|$|R
